1.1 VALIDITY

1.    Internal validity

Are the findings credible for the sample?

 

Threats:

Stable unit treatment value assumption

No interaction effects between subjects: outcome only dependent on treatment

Contamination

Control group access treatment when they should not be able to

Non-compliance

Individuals who are offered a treatment refuse to take it

Hawthorne effect

Participants alter behaviour (subconsciously) by result of merely being part of a study

Placebo effect

Participants alter behaviour by result of conscious and perceived changes

 

2.    External validity

Are the findings credible for extrapolation to the population?

 

Threats:

Sample differs with population

Sample may be small/localised in nature and not representative of the population. Requires enumerative and eliminative induction by repeating RCTs multiple times

Treatment differs with practical implementation

Violation of SUTVA: spill-over effects, general equilibrium effects

Short duration

Short time periods may only reveal immediate surrogate outcomes

2.3 BAD CONTROLS

Good control variables:

         Variables correlated with both independent and dependent variable can reduce ability bias (as long as they are fixed with respect to the independent variable ⇒ 'innate ability')

o    Be aware that more variables can increase attenuation bias if there is CME

         Variables uncorrelated with the independent variable can reduce standard errors

 

Bad control variables:

         Outcomes of the independent variable (e.g. occupation as a control for schooling)

Evaluating Twins methodology

         Schooling differences actually random?

o    Parents may invest more in talented twin, so estimates of e.g. return to schooling would be biased upwards

o    Parents may also invest more in less talented twin, so estimates biased downwards

         Internal validity

o    Measurement error in schooling exacerbated when taking differences (combining two errors)

         Twins develop different abilities over time = epigenetics

         Parental approach for twins differs across families

         External validity

o    Twins are not the same as single children: lower average birth weight, which can affect outcomes

o    Majority of twins due to assisted reproductive technology ⇒ self-selection in families

 

2.5 INSTRUMENTAL VARIATION

See also relevant section in Econometrics

 

When we have omitted variables, we can artificially generate random variation using instruments, that allow us to recover true coefficients using the CIA (in effect, random assignment like in RCTs but with observational data)

 

Structural equation:

 

What makes a valid instrument Z?

1.      Random: Z is as good as randomly assigned with respect to omitted variables

2.      Relevant: Z affects the independent variable X

3.      (Exclusion) Restriction: Z only affects outcome variable Y through X

 

Note that (3) is the troublesome condition: this is an untestable assumption
